04524nam a22007695i 9780812209044DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20132014pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)891520931  a97808122090447 a10.9783/97808122090442doi  a(DE-B1597)449784  a(OCoLC)868967281  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBM501b.S27 2014 7aREL0640002bisacsh1 aSecunda, Shai, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Iranian Talmud :bReading the Bavli in Its Sasanian Context /cShai Secunda. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2013] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDivinations: Rereading Late Ancient Religion00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tNote on abbreviations, citations, and terminology -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. The Sea of Talmud and Its Shore -- tChapter 2. In the Temple and Synagogue -- tChapter 3. Constructing “Them” -- tChapter 4. Closer Than They May Appear -- tChapter 5. In Iran -- tIn Lieu of a Conclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tGeneral Index -- tSource Index -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlthough the Babylonian Talmud, or Bavli, has been a text central and vital to the Jewish canon since the Middle Ages, the context in which it was produced has been poorly understood. Delving deep into Sasanian material culture and literary remains, Shai Secunda pieces together the dynamic world of late antique Iran, providing an unprecedented and accessible overview of the world that shaped the Bavli.Secunda unites the fields of Talmudic scholarship with Old Iranian studies to enable a fresh look at the heterogeneous religious and ethnic communities of pre-Islamic Iran. He analyzes the intercultural dynamics between the Jews and their Persian Zoroastrian neighbors, exploring the complex processes and modes of discourse through which these groups came into contact and considering the ways in which rabbis and Zoroastrian priests perceived one another. Placing the Bavli and examples of Middle Persian literature side by side, the Zoroastrian traces in the former and the discursive and Talmudic qualities of the latter become evident. The Iranian Talmud introduces a substantial and essential shift in the field, setting the stage for further Irano-Talmudic research.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aSassanidsxIntellectual life. 0aZoroastrianism. 4aReligious Studies. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / Talmud.2bisacsh  aJewish Studies.  aReligion.  aReligious Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Religionz978311041358808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Press Complete Package 2014-2015z978311066593240uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220904440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812209044423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812209044.jpg  a978-3-11-041345-8  Penn Press eBook Package Complete Collection  a978-3-11-041358-8  Penn Press eBook Package Religion  a978-3-11-066593-2  University of Pennsylvania Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK